An Erudite's Death<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Dust motes swirled like a swarm of insects in the streams of amber and amethyst light, projected to the marble floors through stained glass set in the library’s ancient dome. Quiet footfalls padded between the racks of tomes, some old, some new, in the ever-expanding archives of Norrathian knowledge. A gasp echoed from the rotunda below, as a newcomer stood entranced by the awe inspiring view of the domed tower’s spiraling interior. The day of such gasps had ended for Caiius Betria many years ago. He was one of many in Erudin who owed their prestige, livelihood and identity to the marble tower and its contents. He was a Librarian.<br>
<br>
Caiius passed through the motes, bathed momentarily in a shimmering coat of light, as he passed between two seldom-used racks of books. The quiet erudite behind him moved with uncommon grace, silent and respectful as he waited for his guide to navigate the sea of pages and tomes. That his visitor was dressed in Oracle blue denoted either access to wealth, or more likely in this case, some experience in the world. Slightly shorter than many in Erud, the fellow seemed pleasant enough and most importantly, knew the one thing that so many did not when they arrived upon the threshold of the High Library of Erudin – the name of the tome he sought. Caiius knew nearly every title in his section, Antiquities and the Combine Era. Many craved the knowledge in the tomes, but knew not the title that would aid them. He detested such ignorant disdain of the efforts of great scholars, and gave to these passing folk little but scorn. But the serious scholar, one who knew the title, or even the author, to these he gave their just due- especially those that discreetly donated as generously as this one had.<br>
<br>
Finally, he stopped and squeezed between the ends of two racks into a small alcove girded by dust covered shelves. Caiius coughed once and motioned for the newcomer to follow him in. The Erudite slipped easily between the eight-foot high bookshelves, and stood in the alcove’s center next to Caiius. He watched the librarian, seemingly unimpressed by the treasury of lost lore surrounding him.<br>
<br>
“Now, that was Excerpts from the Journal of Tesh?” Caiius asked crisply. The Erudite was silent, but nodded his affirmation. Caiius returned the nod, then went directly to the shelf upon which the ancient tome rested. “Of course,” he said as he carefully lifted the worm-eaten book from its resting place, “you realize that you must read it on the tables provided. This particular book is reserved for in Library use, and even then only under the supervision of the Highbrows.” He stood and turned, then saw the Erudite reach into the folds of his robe and withdraw a pouch, moving as if to trade it for the book.<br>
<br>
Caiius understood the gesture at once, and with great affront lifted his chin. “How dare you attempt to bribe me. I am a Librarian of Erud, and you can either obey our rules or go without the knowledge. I accepted your earlier tip as a gift of goodwill, but this! This is nothing but sheer insult.”<br>
<br>
The Erud smiled slowly, then put his pouch away. Caiius nodded, about to speak, but as he did so, the traveler opened a satchel he carried at his side and withdrew a golden rod set with dark, shimmering stones.<br>
<br>
Too late, Caiius felt a twinge of fear build beneath his pride. Still smiling the Erud raised his free hand and muttered a brief incantation. At once, the alcove was filled with scintillating, shimmering colors, swirling about him and leaving him gripped in the bonds of vertigo. <br>
<br>
The shape before him moved slightly, and Caiius managed to mutter, “You want the book! You are an enchanter!” Another incantation pierced the ringing in his ears, and he felt his will dissipate like mist before the summer sun. “Charmed…” he gasped, the sound of his last word, little more than a whisper.<br>
<br>
Unable to control the betrayal of his body, he handed the tome to the Erud, who stood smiling with genuine delight. As much as Caiius loved his books, this Erud loved his glimmercrafts. And now, Caiius, respected by all in Erudin, was nothing but a thrall to the traveler’s whimsy. The blue-robed demon carefully placed the tome in his satchel, then slipped between the racks of books, flawlessly tracing his way back through the maze. Finally, he stood near the end of one rack, and peered down a narrow hallway. Caiius followed, unable to resist.<br>
<br>
Slowly, the Erud looked back to the Librarian of Antiquities, and offered a soft smirk that was at once cruel, sad and apologetic. Caiius approached him, and watched as the golden rod rose to point at a figure emerging from the shadows at the far end of the hall. Softly, in a language that had never before been uttered in the High Library of Erudin, the traveler commanded, “Pet…attack!”<br>
<br>
Caiius charged forward, his hands rising as he neared the purple-robed Feir Dal who had just emerged from a stairwell. Cold and efficient as always, the Erudin Sentry that escorted the visiting dignitary drew his blade and, stepping defensively before the High Elf, allowed Caiius to impale himself upon it as he leapt to attack. Caiius struggled for a moment to reach past the sentry, but the soldier pushed forward with the blade, forcing him back as the hilts pressed against his ruptured abdomen. The sentry pulled his blade back and quickly scanned the area. Caiius, still clawing weakly at the mage, slid off the blade and dropped heavily to the ground. Moving to the rail, he called down for the Captain of the Watch. <br>
<br>
&quot;I apologize for that scene, my lord,&quot; he said to the High Elf. &quot;These librarians sometimes go mad from their monotonous tasks here. Still, they serve a purpose I suppose.&quot; The High Elf waved a hand dismissing the apology, smiled, and walked aroudn the widening pool of blood on the library floor. The sentry removed a towel from his pouch and wiped down his blade, sheathed it, then stepped forward to continue his duties as escort and guide.<br>
<br>
Caiius lay still, his strength leeching away with his blood, his head lolling to one side. Just before darkness took him, he saw an arch of blue light form about a figure in Oracle blue. In that instant he saw the truth of the traveler, he saw the bringer of his death. He mouthed the words, but there were none to hear. As the voice of the apologizing sentry faded down the hall, Caiius watched the last glimmer of sparkling blue fade to slowly to black.<br>
<br>
*** *** *** ***<br>
<br>
The scribe wrote furiously as the Prophet labored beneath the touch of Hate, the images as fresh as if he had witnessed it all himself. The faces shifting, the shimmering light – an unusually vivid vision, even for the Mad One. Finally, the Prophet’s words trailed into the gibberish that often signaled the end of his pain. He was still for several moments, and the scribe looked longingly to the box he used to carry the tools of his trade. When he looked back to the priest, however, his eyes were wide open and seemed covered by a hazy white film.<br>
<br>
“Beware the Mist.” He whispered. “Tell Selilya, beware the Mist.” The scribe wrote the words, remembering them from a previous vision so many months before. The prophet sighed, and fell at once to a deep sleep. Waiting for a few moments to be sure, the scribe quietly rolled up the vellum and stowed them away. Yawning, he put the queries from his mind and left to find his own rest in the dark labrynthe of Neriak.<br>
<br>
Nospiratus K'Thalion<br>
