Re: An Erudite's Death<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
&quot;Perhaps he is awake still,&quot; Faeolin thought. Her duties put aside for the day, she was not quite ready for sleep. Word of Nospiratus' return from the frozen lands of Velious had made her realize how much she missed talking to her old friend. With a little prompting he would willingly talk the night away, and the quiet clinking of glass from her satchel held precisely the sort of prompting he would appreciate.<br>
<br>
The only sounds she heard, were the heavy clanking footsteps of the guards as they patrolled unceasingly through Neriak. She gave and recieved the nods of respect as she passed through her city. The chill wind that blew as she approached the Temple of Innoruuk made her pull her cloak just a bit tighter than she liked to admit. &quot;Will I ever get used to this feeling,&quot; she wondered as shivers ran up her spine. Many times she had passed through the Temple doors, and the result was always the same. <br>
<br>
She had tried to describe it to her friend once, and Nospiratus had only laughed at her. &quot;The eye of Innoruuk is always upon us, it does not stare merely because you have put your heels in one place or another&quot; he had told her. &quot;The reason you feel that way is because you have not been giving enough in your tythes,&quot; he had told her. The result of that conversation was an emptying of her coin purse, and a day polishing his armour as &quot;penance.&quot;<br>
<br>
A couple of turns and his door came in sight. Hefting her pack again, the warrior ground to a halt in front of his door. There was silence within, and she contemplated checking his favorite &quot;tapestry,&quot; to see if he had gone departed that way. He called it that, but she knew that it was not the scenes of Halfling sacrifice that he liked so much, as what lay behind. His hatred of Halflings was well known. Their sacrifice would surely please him to no end, but the secret passage to Neriak Underground and The Blind Fish itself was his real reason for liking the Tapestry so much. <br>
<br>
A light sleeper, he should have awoke to the sound of her knock. She knocked twice more, and worried images crossed her mind. Many of the Harvest had their name on bounty lists, and knowing this she made the decision to enter uninvited. <br>
<br>
A loud snore greeted her as she opened the door, and a quick glance about the room told her all she needed to know.<br>
He had suffered another of his visions tonight, the half empty inkwell on his desk and the candle stubs about the room told her that his scribe had been here and gone already. A strange sensation crossed her heart at that moment, the name was unknown to her, but others would call it pity. A moments decision brought her to take quill and parchment and scribe a note. <br>
<br>
Nospiratus:<br>
<br>
I will leave this satchel for you, since I know you will have need of its contents. Seek me out soon, so we may talk of the events in Velious, and more importantly what you may interpret from tonights trial.<br>
<br>
Faeolin<br>
<br>
Leaving the pack on top of the note, she quietly closed his door and worriedly made her way back to her quarters<br>
